The paper focuses on improving the performance of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) in computer vision tasks, such as image classification, object detection, and segmentation. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also proposes a novel way of processing internal feature representations, which involves adaptively determining the connection status among feature nodes. This aspect of the paper falls under the category of machine learning, specifically deep learning, which is covered by cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper mentions the ability of the proposed method to handle non-Euclidean data, which suggests a potential application in natural language processing (NLP) tasks, covered by cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper presents experimental results on various benchmarks, which indicates a focus on empirical evaluation, falling under the category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
